1 cific qualifications, including organizational and technical capacity, necessary to carry out
2 the purposes described in subsection (1) of this section; and
3 (E) How best to prioritize opportunities to leverage the use of other funding sources,
4 including federal funds and private sector contributions, toward workforce programs and
5 opportunities.
6 (4)(a) If an entity receives funds distributed from a local workforce development board under
7 this section and provides paid work experience to individuals who participate in the program es-
8 tablished under this section, the entity shall:
9 (A) Notwithstanding ORS 653.025 [and subsection (2)(h) of this section], pay wages to individuals
10 participating in the program at a rate that is:
11 (i) Equivalent to an entry-level training wage as determined by the entity pursuant to paragraph
12 (b) of this subsection; and
13 (ii) In alignment with the wage progression schedule established by the entity under subpara-
14 graph (B) of this paragraph;
15 (B) Establish a wage progression schedule that includes the step progression requirements and
16 the rate calculation formula upon which the entity shall make determinations about a participating
17 individual’s eligibility to increase the individual’s wage rate from an entry-level training wage to a
18 wage rate that is equivalent to the average area wage standard for an hour’s work in the same trade
19 or occupation in the locality where the labor is performed;
20 (C) Develop a training plan for individuals participating in the program that includes, at a
21 minimum:
22 (i) The entry-level training wage that will be paid to the individual;
23 (ii) A statement that the individual shall be paid according to the wage progression schedule
24 established by the entity, along with a description of the requirements that the individual must meet
25 in order to progress to a higher wage rate under the wage progression schedule;
26 (iii) A statement that the entry-level training wage paid to the individual may not be less than
27 the federal minimum wage rate or the applicable state minimum wage rate, whichever is greater;
28 and
29 (iv) A statement explaining that the entry-level training wage paid to the individual is a mini-
30 mum standard and that a higher wage rate shall be paid to the individual if so required under other
31 applicable federal or state laws, regulations or a collective bargaining agreement; and
32 (D) Provide each individual participating in the program with a copy of the training plan de-
33 scribed in subparagraph (C) of this paragraph on the date on which the individual first begins par-
34 ticipating in the program.
35 (b) For purposes of paragraph (a)(A) of this subsection, the entry-level training wage shall be a
36 percentage amount of the average area wage standard for an hour’s work in the same trade or oc-
37 cupation in the locality where the labor is performed, but in no event may the entry-level training
38 wage be less than the applicable state minimum wage rate under ORS 653.025.
39 (c) Each individual who performs work for an entity described in this subsection shall be con-
40 sidered an employee of the entity for purposes of state wage and hour laws and state laws prohib-
41 iting employment discrimination and retaliation.
42 (5)(a) As used in this subsection, “SNAP Employment and Training Program” means the em-
43 ployment and training component of the federal Supplemental Nutrition Assistance Program under
44 7 U.S.C. 2015(d)(4).
45 (b) To the extent possible, the Department of Human Services shall:
